# HTML INTERVIEW QUESTIONS & ANSWERS

Complete guide from Beginner to Expert

---

## Beginner Level Questions

### Q1: What is HTML and what does it do?

**Answer:**

HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the standard markup language for creating web pages. It provides the structure and content of web applications.

**What HTML does:**
- Creates structure and hierarchy (headings, paragraphs, sections)
- Embeds images, videos, and other media
- Creates links between pages and websites
- Creates forms for user input
- Adds metadata for SEO and accessibility
- Provides semantic meaning to content

**HTML in context:**
```
HTML = Structure & Content (skeleton)
CSS  = Styling & Layout (appearance)
JS   = Behavior & Interactivity (functionality)
```

**Example:**
```html
<h1>Welcome</h1>
<p>This is a paragraph</p>
```

The browser displays: "Welcome" as heading, "This is a paragraph" as text below it.

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ HTML is NOT a programming language (no logic)
- ✓ HTML is markup language (describes content)
- ✓ Browser interprets HTML and renders it
- ✓ Every website starts with HTML

---

### Q2: What's the difference between an element and a tag?

**Answer:**

**Tag:** The markup syntax itself (the code you write)
**Element:** The complete unit including opening tag, content, and closing tag

```html
<!-- Tags (just the syntax) -->
<p>    ← Opening tag
</p>   ← Closing tag

<!-- Element (complete unit) -->
<p>This is content</p>  ← Complete element
 ↑                    ↑
Opening tag        Closing tag
```

**Examples:**

```html
<!-- This is an element -->
<h1>Title</h1>

<!-- This is an element -->
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Description">

<!-- This is an element -->
<a href="https://example.com">Link</a>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Tag = Just the markup syntax
- ✓ Element = Tag + Content + Everything
- ✓ Self-closing tags (img, br, hr) are also elements
- ✓ All elements have semantic meaning

---

### Q3: What's the purpose of semantic HTML?

**Answer:**

Semantic HTML uses elements that clearly describe their meaning and purpose to both browsers and developers.

**Example:**

```html
<!-- ✗ Non-semantic (meaningless divs) -->
<div class="header">
  <div class="navigation">
    <a href="/">Home</a>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ✓ Semantic (meaningful elements) -->
<header>
  <nav>
    <a href="/">Home</a>
  </nav>
</header>
```

**Benefits:**

1. **SEO**: Search engines understand page structure
2. **Accessibility**: Screen readers understand content hierarchy
3. **Maintenance**: Code is self-documenting
4. **Mobile**: Devices render semantic HTML better
5. **Future-proof**: Standards-based approach

**Semantic Elements:**
```html
<header>   - Page header
<nav>      - Navigation
<main>     - Main content
<section>  - Thematic section
<article>  - Independent content
<aside>    - Sidebar
<footer>   - Page footer
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Semantic > Generic (use header not div class="header")
- ✓ Improves SEO automatically
- ✓ Better accessibility for screen readers
- ✓ Easier to maintain and understand
- ✓ Mobile devices optimize semantic HTML

---

### Q4: What is the difference between block and inline elements?

**Answer:**

**Block elements:** Take full width, create line breaks before and after

```html
<p>Block element</p>        <!-- Full width, line break -->
<p>Another block element</p> <!-- Appears below previous -->

Block elements:
- <div>
- <p>
- <h1>-<h6>
- <section>
- <article>
- <header>
- <footer>
```

**Inline elements:** Only take necessary width, no line breaks

```html
<span>Inline element</span>
<span>Another inline element</span>  <!-- Appears beside previous -->

Inline elements:
- <span>
- <a>
- <strong>
- <em>
- <img>
- <button>
```

**Visual Difference:**

```html
<!-- Block: Each takes full width -->
<p>Block 1</p>
<p>Block 2</p>

<!-- Inline: Side by side -->
<span>Inline 1</span>
<span>Inline 2</span>

<!-- Inline-block: Best of both worlds -->
<span style="display: inline-block; width: 200px;">Inline-block</span>
<span style="display: inline-block; width: 200px;">Inline-block</span>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Block: Full width, line breaks (p, div, h1)
- ✓ Inline: Only needed width, no breaks (span, a, strong)
- ✓ Inline-block: Both properties combined
- ✓ Use CSS to change display property

---

### Q5: What are HTML attributes and give examples?

**Answer:**

Attributes provide additional information about elements. They're always in the opening tag.

```html
<tagname attributename="value">Content</tagname>
```

**Common Attributes:**

```html
<!-- Global attributes (work on all elements) -->
<element id="unique-id">                    <!-- Unique identifier -->
<element class="class-name">                <!-- CSS class -->
<element style="color: red;">               <!-- Inline style -->
<element title="Tooltip text">              <!-- Hover tooltip -->
<element data-custom="value">               <!-- Custom data -->

<!-- Specific attributes -->
<a href="https://example.com">              <!-- Link target -->
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Description">     <!-- Image source and alt -->
<form method="POST" action="/submit">       <!-- Form method and action -->
<input type="email" required>               <!-- Input type and validation -->
```

**Example with Multiple Attributes:**

```html
<a href="https://example.com" 
   title="Visit Example"
   class="external-link"
   target="_blank">
  Visit Example
</a>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Attributes provide metadata about elements
- ✓ Format: name="value" (with quotes)
- ✓ Multiple attributes allowed
- ✓ Some are optional, some required
- ✓ Attributes don't appear in browser, affect element behavior

---

## Intermediate Level Questions

### Q6: What's the difference between id and class attributes?

**Answer:**

**id (Identifier):** Unique, one per page

```html
<!-- Only ONE element with id="main-content" on entire page -->
<div id="main-content">
  Main content here
</div>

<!-- Can link to with anchor -->
<a href="#main-content">Jump to main</a>

<!-- JavaScript access -->
<script>
const element = document.getElementById('main-content');
</script>
```

**class:** Reusable, multiple per page

```html
<!-- Multiple elements can have same class -->
<p class="highlight">Important text 1</p>
<p class="highlight">Important text 2</p>

<!-- One element can have multiple classes -->
<p class="highlight important urgent">Very important</p>

<!-- CSS styling -->
<style>
.highlight { background-color: yellow; }
.important { font-weight: bold; }
</style>

<!-- JavaScript access (all elements) -->
<script>
const elements = document.querySelectorAll('.highlight');
</script>
```

**Comparison:**

| Feature | id | class |
|---------|----|----|
| Uniqueness | One per page | Multiple allowed |
| Usage | Unique identifiers | Styling/grouping |
| CSS Specificity | Higher | Lower |
| JavaScript | getElementById() | querySelector()/getElementsByClassName() |
| Best Practice | Use sparingly | Use for styling |

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ id: Unique identifier (one per page)
- ✓ class: Reusable classifier (multiple per page)
- ✓ Use class for styling, id for unique elements
- ✓ id has higher CSS specificity
- ✓ Never duplicate ids on same page

---

### Q7: What is semantic HTML and why is it important?

**Answer:**

Semantic HTML uses meaningful element names that describe the content's purpose.

**Non-Semantic vs Semantic:**

```html
<!-- ✗ Non-semantic: Meaningless generic tags -->
<div class="header">
  <div class="title">Article</div>
  <div class="date">2024-12-24</div>
</div>

<!-- ✓ Semantic: Meaningful tags -->
<header>
  <h1>Article</h1>
  <time datetime="2024-12-24">December 24, 2024</time>
</header>
```

**Why It's Important:**

1. **SEO**: Search engines understand structure
2. **Accessibility**: Screen readers understand content
3. **Mobile**: Devices optimize semantic HTML
4. **Maintenance**: Developers understand code quickly
5. **Standards**: Future-proof approach

**Semantic Elements and Their Purpose:**

```html
<header>      - Page/section header
<nav>         - Navigation menu
<main>        - Main content of page
<section>     - Thematic grouping
<article>     - Independent, self-contained content
<aside>       - Sidebar or supplementary content
<footer>      - Page/section footer
<figure>      - Image with caption
<figcaption>  - Caption for figure
<time>        - Date/time
<mark>        - Highlighted text
```

**Real Example:**

```html
<!-- Article with semantic markup -->
<article>
  <header>
    <h1>Article Title</h1>
    <time datetime="2024-12-24">December 24, 2024</time>
    <span>By Author Name</span>
  </header>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>Content here</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Main Content</h2>
    <p>Content here</p>
  </section>
  
  <footer>
    <p>Article footer</p>
  </footer>
</article>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Use semantic tags (header, nav, main, footer, article)
- ✓ Improves SEO and accessibility automatically
- ✓ Code is self-documenting
- ✓ Better mobile rendering
- ✓ Semantic first, then use divs if needed

---

### Q8: How do you make images responsive?

**Answer:**

Responsive images adapt to different screen sizes without losing quality or loading unnecessarily large files.

**Method 1: CSS (simplest)**

```html
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Description" style="max-width: 100%;">

<!-- Or in CSS -->
<style>
img {
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}
</style>
```

**Method 2: srcset (HTML5)**

```html
<!-- Browser chooses best image based on device -->
<img src="image-small.jpg"
     srcset="image-small.jpg 480w,
             image-medium.jpg 768w,
             image-large.jpg 1200w"
     sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw,
            (max-width: 1200px) 80vw,
            60vw"
     alt="Description">
```

How it works:
- On mobile (< 600px): Load image-small.jpg (480w)
- On tablet (< 1200px): Load image-medium.jpg (768w)
- On desktop: Load image-large.jpg (1200w)

**Method 3: Picture Element (art direction)**

```html
<!-- Different images for different screen sizes -->
<picture>
  <source media="(max-width: 600px)" srcset="image-mobile.jpg">
  <source media="(max-width: 1200px)" srcset="image-tablet.jpg">
  <img src="image-desktop.jpg" alt="Description">
</picture>
```

Use when: You want different cropping/composition for different devices

**Method 4: Modern Image Formats**

```html
<!-- Use WebP (smaller file size), fallback to PNG -->
<picture>
  <source srcset="image.webp" type="image/webp">
  <source srcset="image.png" type="image/png">
  <img src="image.png" alt="Description">
</picture>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ srcset: Different resolutions of same image
- ✓ picture: Different images for different layouts
- ✓ Use modern formats (WebP) for smaller files
- ✓ Always provide alt text
- ✓ Lazy load images when below the fold

---

### Q9: What's the importance of alt text?

**Answer:**

Alt text describes images for users who can't see them and helps search engines understand images.

**Why It Matters:**

```
1. Accessibility: Screen readers read alt text aloud
2. SEO: Search engines use alt text to understand images
3. Broken Images: Alt text shows when image fails to load
4. Mobile: Shows when images disabled (data saving mode)
```

**Good Alt Text:**

```html
<!-- ✓ GOOD: Descriptive, contextual -->
<img src="chart.jpg" alt="Sales growth chart showing 25% increase from Q1 to Q2 2024">

<!-- ✗ BAD: Too generic -->
<img src="chart.jpg" alt="chart">

<!-- ✗ BAD: Redundant (repeats nearby text) -->
<img src="logo.png" alt="Company Logo">
<h1>Company Logo</h1>

<!-- ✓ GOOD: Decorative images (empty alt) -->
<img src="decorative-line.png" alt="">

<!-- ✓ GOOD: Icon with meaning -->
<span aria-hidden="true">⭐</span> 5 Stars
<!-- Hidden from accessibility, shown visually -->

<!-- ✓ GOOD: Image as link -->
<a href="/home" aria-label="Home page">
  <img src="home-icon.png" alt="">
</a>
```

**Best Practices:**

```
✓ Be descriptive but concise (< 125 chars)
✓ Describe content, not just "image"
✓ Don't start with "image of" or "picture of"
✓ Empty alt="" for purely decorative images
✓ Include relevant details for important images
✓ Don't keyword stuff
```

**Examples:**

```html
<!-- ✗ Poor: Too generic -->
<img src="photo.jpg" alt="photo">

<!-- ✓ Better: Descriptive -->
<img src="hiking-trail.jpg" alt="Rocky mountain hiking trail with pine trees">

<!-- ✗ Poor: Keyword stuffing -->
<img src="shoes.jpg" alt="red shoes, blue shoes, leather shoes, discount shoes">

<!-- ✓ Better: Natural description -->
<img src="shoes.jpg" alt="Red leather hiking boots with waterproof coating">
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Alt text is mandatory for accessibility
- ✓ Screen readers rely on alt text
- ✓ Improves SEO
- ✓ Shows if image fails to load
- ✓ Be descriptive but natural

---

## Advanced Level Questions

### Q10: Explain the HTML document structure and DOCTYPE.

**Answer:**

Proper HTML document structure tells browsers how to interpret the file.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>           <!-- Declare document type -->
<html lang="en">          <!-- Root element, language -->
  <head>                  <!-- Metadata container -->
    <meta charset="UTF-8">                    <!-- Character encoding -->
    <meta name="viewport"
          content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">  <!-- Mobile support -->
    <title>Page Title</title>                  <!-- Browser tab title -->
  </head>
  
  <body>                  <!-- Visible content -->
    <header>
      <h1>Page Title</h1>
    </header>
    
    <main>
      <!-- Main content -->
    </main>
    
    <footer>
      <!-- Footer -->
    </footer>
  </body>
</html>
```

**DOCTYPE Explanation:**

```html
<!-- HTML5 DOCTYPE (current standard) -->
<!DOCTYPE html>

<!-- Older versions (avoid) -->
<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN">
```

DOCTYPE tells browser:
- How to interpret the page
- What HTML version is used
- How to render elements

**Head vs Body:**

```html
<head>
  <!-- NOT visible to users -->
  <title>Shown in browser tab</title>
  <meta name="description">  <!-- Used by search engines -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
  <script src="app.js"></script>
</head>

<body>
  <!-- VISIBLE to users -->
  <h1>Visible heading</h1>
  <p>Visible paragraph</p>
</body>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ DOCTYPE must be first line
- ✓ Use HTML5 DOCTYPE (<!DOCTYPE html>)
- ✓ Head: Metadata, styles, scripts (hidden)
- ✓ Body: Content (visible)
- ✓ One lang attribute on html tag
- ✓ Always include charset meta tag
- ✓ Always include viewport meta tag

---

### Q11: What are HTML5 and what new features does it add?

**Answer:**

HTML5 is the current standard for HTML, introduced in 2014. It brought significant new capabilities.

**New HTML5 Elements:**

```html
<!-- Semantic elements -->
<header>      - Page header
<nav>         - Navigation
<main>        - Main content
<section>     - Thematic section
<article>     - Independent article
<aside>       - Sidebar
<footer>      - Footer
<figure>      - Figure with caption
<figcaption>  - Figure caption
<time>        - Date/time

<!-- Media elements (no plugins needed) -->
<audio>       - Audio playback
<video>       - Video playback
<source>      - Media source
<track>       - Captions/subtitles

<!-- Interactive -->
<canvas>      - Drawing surface
<svg>         - Vector graphics
<details>     - Collapsible content
<summary>     - Summary/heading
```

**New Input Types:**

```html
<input type="email">              <!-- Email validation -->
<input type="number">             <!-- Number input -->
<input type="range">              <!-- Slider -->
<input type="date">               <!-- Date picker -->
<input type="time">               <!-- Time picker -->
<input type="color">              <!-- Color picker -->
<input type="search">             <!-- Search field -->
<input type="tel">                <!-- Telephone -->
<input type="url">                <!-- URL -->
```

**New APIs:**

```html
<!-- Canvas: Draw graphics -->
<canvas id="myCanvas"></canvas>
<script>
const canvas = document.getElementById('myCanvas');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
ctx.fillStyle = 'red';
ctx.fillRect(10, 10, 100, 100);
</script>

<!-- Geolocation: Get user location -->
navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(function(position) {
  console.log(position.coords.latitude);
  console.log(position.coords.longitude);
});

<!-- LocalStorage: Persistent storage -->
localStorage.setItem('user', 'John');
const user = localStorage.getItem('user');

<!-- Offline capability -->
<html manifest="offline.appcache">
```

**Validation Attributes:**

```html
<input type="email" required>                  <!-- Must be filled -->
<input type="text" minlength="3" maxlength="20">  <!-- Length limits -->
<input type="number" min="0" max="100">        <!-- Number range -->
<input type="text" pattern="[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{3}">  <!-- Regex pattern -->
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ HTML5 is current standard (still evolving)
- ✓ Added semantic elements (header, nav, main, article)
- ✓ Native audio/video (no plugins)
- ✓ Canvas for drawing
- ✓ New input types with validation
- ✓ APIs for geolocation, storage, offline
- ✓ Better accessibility support (ARIA)

---

### Q12: What is ARIA and when should you use it?

**Answer:**

ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) provides attributes to enhance accessibility for complex interactive components.

**ARIA Attributes:**

```html
<!-- role: Define element purpose -->
<div role="button">Click me</div>
<div role="alert">Error message</div>
<div role="progressbar"></div>

<!-- aria-label: Invisible label -->
<button aria-label="Close menu">×</button>

<!-- aria-describedby: Link to description -->
<input type="text" aria-describedby="pwd-hint">
<small id="pwd-hint">At least 8 characters</small>

<!-- aria-live: Announce updates to screen readers -->
<div aria-live="polite">
  5 new messages
</div>

<!-- aria-expanded: Show expand/collapse state -->
<button aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="menu">
  Menu
</button>
<div id="menu" hidden>Menu content</div>

<!-- aria-required: Mark required fields -->
<input type="text" aria-required="true">

<!-- aria-hidden: Hide from accessibility tree -->
<span aria-hidden="true">★★★★★</span>
```

**When to Use ARIA:**

```html
<!-- ✓ Use: Custom interactive components -->
<div role="slider" aria-valuenow="50" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="100">
  <!-- Custom slider -->
</div>

<!-- ✓ Use: Dynamic content updates -->
<div aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">
  Loading... (updates as content loads)
</div>

<!-- ✗ Avoid: Use semantic HTML instead -->
<!-- Don't: <div role="button">Click</div> -->
<!-- Do: <button>Click</button> -->

<!-- ✗ Avoid: Over-using ARIA -->
<div role="paragraph">Just a paragraph</div>  <!-- Use <p> instead -->
```

**Common ARIA Patterns:**

```html
<!-- Modal dialog -->
<div role="alertdialog" aria-labelledby="dialog-title" aria-modal="true">
  <h2 id="dialog-title">Confirm action</h2>
  <p>Are you sure?</p>
</div>

<!-- Menu -->
<button aria-haspopup="true" aria-expanded="false">Menu</button>
<ul role="menu">
  <li role="menuitem"><a href="/">Home</a></li>
  <li role="menuitem"><a href="/about">About</a></li>
</ul>

<!-- Tabs -->
<div role="tablist">
  <button role="tab" aria-selected="true" aria-controls="panel1">Tab 1</button>
  <button role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="panel2">Tab 2</button>
</div>
<div role="tabpanel" id="panel1">Content 1</div>
<div role="tabpanel" id="panel2" hidden>Content 2</div>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ ARIA = Accessible Rich Internet Applications
- ✓ Use for complex interactive components
- ✓ First rule: Use semantic HTML, then ARIA
- ✓ ARIA doesn't add functionality, only accessibility
- ✓ Requires proper keyboard handling with JavaScript
- ✓ Test with screen readers (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)

---

### Q13: How do you optimize HTML for performance?

**Answer:**

Performance optimization improves page load speed and user experience.

**1. Script Loading:**

```html
<!-- ✗ Bad: Blocks page rendering -->
<head>
  <script src="app.js"></script>
</head>

<!-- ✓ Good: Defer loading until DOM ready -->
<script src="app.js" defer></script>

<!-- ✓ Good: Async for non-critical scripts -->
<script src="analytics.js" async></script>

<!-- ✓ Good: Put scripts at end of body -->
<body>
  <!-- Content -->
  <script src="app.js"></script>
</body>
```

**2. Image Optimization:**

```html
<!-- ✗ Load large images on mobile -->
<img src="desktop-image.jpg">

<!-- ✓ Use responsive images -->
<img src="image-small.jpg"
     srcset="image-medium.jpg 768w, image-large.jpg 1200w"
     sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 50vw"
     alt="Description">

<!-- ✓ Lazy load below-the-fold images -->
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Description" loading="lazy">

<!-- ✓ Use modern formats -->
<picture>
  <source srcset="image.webp" type="image/webp">
  <img src="image.jpg" alt="Description">
</picture>
```

**3. Resource Preloading:**

```html
<!-- Preload critical resources -->
<link rel="preload" href="critical.css" as="style">
<link rel="preload" href="font.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin>

<!-- Prefetch future resources -->
<link rel="prefetch" href="next-page.html">

<!-- DNS prefetch for external domains -->
<link rel="dns-prefetch" href="//cdn.example.com">

<!-- Preconnect for critical domains -->
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
```

**4. CSS Optimization:**

```html
<!-- ✓ Critical CSS inline -->
<style>
  body { font-family: Arial; }
  h1 { color: blue; }
</style>

<!-- Defer non-critical CSS -->
<link rel="preload" href="style.css" as="style" onload="this.onload=null;this.rel='stylesheet'">
<noscript><link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css"></noscript>
```

**5. Metadata:**

```html
<!-- Proper charset (affects parsing) -->
<meta charset="UTF-8">

<!-- Viewport (prevents slowdown on mobile) -->
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">

<!-- Reduce DNS lookups -->
<meta http-equiv="x-ua-compatible" content="IE=edge">
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ defer: Scripts load after DOM
- ✓ async: Scripts load in parallel
- ✓ Responsive images reduce downloads
- ✓ Lazy loading defers off-screen images
- ✓ Preload critical resources
- ✓ Minimize render-blocking resources
- ✓ Use modern image formats (WebP)

---

### Q14: What's the difference between semantic and non-semantic HTML?

**Answer:**

**Non-Semantic HTML:** Generic tags that don't describe meaning

```html
<div class="header">
  <div class="nav">
    <a href="/">Home</a>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <div class="article">
    <div class="title">Article Title</div>
    <div class="body">Content</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="footer">
  <p>&copy; 2024</p>
</div>
```

Problems:
- Divs have no meaning (just generic containers)
- Developers must read CSS to understand structure
- Screen readers can't understand layout
- SEO engines struggle to parse structure

**Semantic HTML:** Meaningful tags that describe purpose

```html
<header>
  <nav>
    <a href="/">Home</a>
  </nav>
</header>

<main>
  <article>
    <h1>Article Title</h1>
    <p>Content</p>
  </article>
</main>

<footer>
  <p>&copy; 2024</p>
</footer>
```

Benefits:
- Tags describe their purpose
- Self-documenting code
- Screen readers understand structure
- SEO engines parse easily
- Mobile browsers optimize rendering

**Comparison Table:**

| Aspect | Non-Semantic | Semantic |
|--------|--------------|----------|
| Meaning | None (divs) | Clear purpose |
| SEO | Worse | Better |
| Accessibility | Poor | Excellent |
| Readability | Unclear | Self-documenting |
| Mobile | Generic rendering | Optimized |

**Semantic Elements Reference:**

```html
<header>       - Page/section header
<nav>          - Navigation links
<main>         - Main content
<section>      - Thematic grouping
<article>      - Independent content
<aside>        - Sidebar/supplementary
<footer>       - Page/section footer
<figure>       - Image with caption
<figcaption>   - Figure caption
<time>         - Date/time
<mark>         - Highlighted text
<strong>       - Important (not just bold)
<em>           - Emphasized (not just italic)
<blockquote>   - Quote with attribution
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Semantic tags describe content purpose
- ✓ Improves SEO automatically
- ✓ Better accessibility for screen readers
- ✓ Code is self-documenting
- ✓ Mobile devices optimize semantic HTML
- ✓ Use semantic first, divs when needed

---

### Q15: How do you structure a proper HTML form?

**Answer:**

Proper form structure ensures accessibility, usability, and proper functionality.

**Complete Form Structure:**

```html
<form action="/submit" method="POST" id="contact-form">
  <!-- Fieldset groups related inputs -->
  <fieldset>
    <legend>Personal Information</legend>
    
    <!-- Each input needs a label -->
    <div class="form-group">
      <label for="name">Name *</label>
      <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required>
      <span class="error" id="name-error"></span>
    </div>
    
    <div class="form-group">
      <label for="email">Email *</label>
      <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>
      <span class="error" id="email-error"></span>
    </div>
  </fieldset>
  
  <!-- Another fieldset for different section -->
  <fieldset>
    <legend>Message</legend>
    
    <div class="form-group">
      <label for="subject">Subject *</label>
      <input type="text" id="subject" name="subject" required>
    </div>
    
    <div class="form-group">
      <label for="message">Message *</label>
      <textarea id="message" name="message" rows="5" required></textarea>
    </div>
  </fieldset>
  
  <!-- Buttons -->
  <div class="form-actions">
    <button type="submit">Send</button>
    <button type="reset">Clear</button>
  </div>
</form>
```

**Key Elements Explained:**

```html
<!-- Form element: Container for inputs -->
<form action="/endpoint" method="POST">

<!-- Fieldset: Groups related inputs -->
<fieldset>

<!-- Legend: Fieldset title (accessibility) -->
<legend>Section Title</legend>

<!-- Label: Associates text with input -->
<label for="name">Name:</label>
<input id="name" name="name">
<!-- for/id must match -->

<!-- Input types with validation -->
<input type="email" required>
<input type="text" minlength="3" maxlength="20">
<input type="number" min="0" max="100">

<!-- Textarea for multi-line -->
<textarea name="message" rows="5"></textarea>

<!-- Select for dropdown -->
<select name="country">
  <option value="">-- Select --</option>
  <option value="us">USA</option>
</select>

<!-- Checkbox: Multiple selections -->
<input type="checkbox" name="interests" value="sports">
<label for="sports">Sports</label>

<!-- Radio: Single selection -->
<input type="radio" name="size" value="small">
<label for="small">Small</label>

<!-- Submit button -->
<button type="submit">Submit</button>
```

**Accessibility Best Practices:**

```html
<!-- ✓ Always use labels -->
<label for="email">Email:</label>
<input id="email" type="email">

<!-- ✓ Use fieldsets for grouping -->
<fieldset>
  <legend>Select options:</legend>
  <!-- Checkboxes here -->
</fieldset>

<!-- ✓ Help text for complex fields -->
<label for="password">Password:</label>
<input id="password" type="password" aria-describedby="pwd-help">
<small id="pwd-help">At least 8 characters, one number</small>

<!-- ✓ Error messages linked to fields -->
<input id="email" type="email" aria-describedby="email-error">
<span id="email-error" role="alert">Invalid email</span>

<!-- ✓ Mark required fields -->
<label for="name">Name <span aria-label="required">*</span></label>
<input id="name" name="name" required>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Every input needs a label (for accessibility)
- ✓ Use fieldsets to group related inputs
- ✓ Legend describes fieldset (accessibility)
- ✓ Use correct input types (HTML5)
- ✓ Validate with HTML5 attributes first
- ✓ Add help text for complex fields
- ✓ Link error messages to inputs
- ✓ Mark required fields clearly

---

## Expert Level Questions

### Q16: Explain the concept of progressive enhancement.

**Answer:**

Progressive enhancement means building websites that work with HTML first, then enhanced with CSS and JavaScript.

**Three Layers:**

```
HTML (Foundation) - Works everywhere
    ↓
CSS (Enhancement) - Better presentation
    ↓
JavaScript (Enhancement) - Better interaction
```

**Example:**

```html
<!-- Layer 1: HTML (works without CSS/JS) -->
<form action="/search" method="GET">
  <input type="search" name="q" placeholder="Search...">
  <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<!-- Form works on all devices:
  - Desktop: All features
  - Slow internet: Basic functionality
  - JavaScript disabled: Still works
  - Old browsers: Still works -->

<!-- Layer 2: CSS (better presentation) -->
<style>
form {
  display: flex;
  gap: 10px;
}

input {
  flex: 1;
  padding: 8px;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  border-radius: 4px;
}

button {
  padding: 8px 16px;
  background-color: blue;
  color: white;
  border: none;
  cursor: pointer;
}
</style>

<!-- Layer 3: JavaScript (better interaction) -->
<script>
document.querySelector('form').addEventListener('submit', function(e) {
  e.preventDefault();
  
  // Live search instead of page reload
  const query = this.querySelector('input').value;
  performLiveSearch(query);
});
</script>
```

**Benefits:**

```
1. Accessibility: Works without JavaScript
2. Performance: Basic features load fast
3. Reliability: Doesn't break on JS error
4. SEO: Search engines can index content
5. User Experience: Works on all devices
6. Maintenance: Separate concerns
```

**Anti-Pattern (Don't Do This):**

```html
<!-- ✗ Doesn't work without JavaScript -->
<div onclick="search()" class="button">
  Search
</div>

<!-- ✓ Progressive Enhancement -->
<button type="submit">Search</button>
<!-- CSS makes it look good -->
<!-- JavaScript adds live search -->
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ HTML: Core functionality (always works)
- ✓ CSS: Enhancement (presentation)
- ✓ JavaScript: Enhancement (interactivity)
- ✓ Each layer works independently
- ✓ Gracefully degrades without JavaScript
- ✓ Better accessibility and SEO

---

### Q17: What is the difference between client-side and server-side HTML rendering?

**Answer:**

**Client-Side Rendering:** Browser renders HTML (JavaScript)

```html
<!-- Empty HTML on server -->
<body>
  <div id="app"></div>
  <script src="react.js"></script>
</body>

<!-- Browser receives HTML, downloads React,
     React renders content dynamically -->

Pros:
- Dynamic, interactive UX
- Reduces server load
- Smooth page transitions

Cons:
- Slower initial load (JS download + execution)
- Blank screen on slow connection
- SEO challenges (content generated by JS)
- Uses more device resources
```

**Server-Side Rendering:** Server generates HTML

```html
<!-- Server generates complete HTML -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head><title>Page</title></head>
<body>
  <h1>Content from server</h1>
  <p>All content already here</p>
</body>
</html>

<!-- Browser receives ready-to-display HTML -->

Pros:
- Fast initial load
- Content visible immediately
- Good for SEO
- Works without JavaScript

Cons:
- Slower page transitions
- Higher server load
- Full page reload on navigation
- Less dynamic interaction
```

**Hybrid Approach (Modern Standard):**

```html
<!-- Server sends HTML -->
<!-- JavaScript enhances interactivity -->

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <!-- Static HTML from server -->
  <h1>Welcome</h1>
  
  <!-- JavaScript enhances -->
  <script src="app.js"></script>
</body>
</html>

Combines best of both:
- Fast initial load (HTML from server)
- Good interactivity (JavaScript enhancement)
- Good SEO (content in HTML)
- Good UX (dynamic updates)
```

**Comparison:**

| Aspect | CSR | SSR | Hybrid |
|--------|-----|-----|--------|
| Initial Load | Slow | Fast | Fast |
| Interactivity | High | Low | High |
| SEO | Challenging | Excellent | Excellent |
| Server Load | Low | High | Medium |
| Best For | Single Page Apps | Content Sites | Modern Apps |

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ CSR: Slow initial, fast after
- ✓ SSR: Fast initial, less interactive
- ✓ Hybrid: Best balance
- ✓ Modern approach: Server + Client rendering
- ✓ HTML from server, JavaScript enhances

---

### Q18: How do you implement structured data (Schema.org)?

**Answer:**

Structured data helps search engines understand page content and enables rich search results.

**Example: Article**

```html
<article itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Article">
  <!-- Article metadata -->
  <h1 itemprop="headline">How to Learn HTML</h1>
  
  <!-- Author -->
  <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
    By <span itemprop="name">John Doe</span>
  </span>
  
  <!-- Publication date -->
  <time itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2024-12-24">
    December 24, 2024
  </time>
  
  <!-- Modified date -->
  <time itemprop="dateModified" datetime="2024-12-25">
    Updated: December 25, 2024
  </time>
  
  <!-- Featured image -->
  <img itemprop="image" src="article-image.jpg" alt="Article image">
  
  <!-- Article description/content -->
  <p itemprop="articleBody">
    Article content here...
  </p>
</article>
```

**Example: Recipe**

```html
<div itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Recipe">
  <h1 itemprop="name">Chocolate Cake</h1>
  
  <img itemprop="image" src="cake.jpg" alt="Cake">
  
  <p itemprop="description">Delicious homemade chocolate cake</p>
  
  <!-- Rating -->
  <div itemprop="aggregateRating" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/AggregateRating">
    <span itemprop="ratingValue">4.5</span>
    out of <span itemprop="bestRating">5</span>
    stars from <span itemprop="ratingCount">100</span> reviews
  </div>
  
  <!-- Time info -->
  <time itemprop="prepTime" datetime="PT20M">20 minutes prep</time>
  <time itemprop="cookTime" datetime="PT30M">30 minutes cook</time>
  
  <!-- Ingredients -->
  <h3>Ingredients:</h3>
  <ul>
    <li itemprop="recipeIngredient">2 cups flour</li>
    <li itemprop="recipeIngredient">1 cup sugar</li>
  </ul>
  
  <!-- Instructions -->
  <h3>Instructions:</h3>
  <ol>
    <li itemprop="recipeInstructions">Mix ingredients</li>
    <li itemprop="recipeInstructions">Bake at 350°F</li>
  </ol>
  
  <!-- Yield -->
  <span itemprop="recipeYield">8 servings</span>
</div>
```

**Example: Product**

```html
<div itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Product">
  <h1 itemprop="name">Wireless Headphones</h1>
  
  <!-- Image -->
  <img itemprop="image" src="headphones.jpg" alt="Headphones">
  
  <!-- Description -->
  <p itemprop="description">Premium wireless headphones</p>
  
  <!-- Rating -->
  <div itemprop="aggregateRating" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/AggregateRating">
    <span itemprop="ratingValue">4.8</span> / <span itemprop="bestRating">5</span>
    (<span itemprop="ratingCount">500</span> reviews)
  </div>
  
  <!-- Price -->
  <div itemprop="offers" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Offer">
    Price: $<span itemprop="price">199.99</span>
    Currency: <span itemprop="priceCurrency">USD</span>
    In Stock: <span itemprop="availability">InStock</span>
  </div>
</div>
```

**Validation:**

```
1. Use Google Rich Results Test
2. Validate with Schema.org validator
3. Check in Google Search Console
4. Look for rich snippet in search results
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Structured data helps search engines understand content
- ✓ Enables rich search results (ratings, prices, etc.)
- ✓ Uses schema.org standards
- ✓ Microdata format (itemscope, itemtype, itemprop)
- ✓ Improves CTR in search results
- ✓ Validate structured data

---

### Q19: What are data attributes (data-*) and how do you use them?

**Answer:**

Data attributes store custom data on HTML elements. They're not displayed but can be accessed via JavaScript.

**Basic Usage:**

```html
<!-- Store data on elements -->
<div id="product" 
     data-product-id="123"
     data-product-name="Laptop"
     data-product-price="999.99">
  Laptop
</div>

<!-- Access via JavaScript -->
<script>
const element = document.getElementById('product');

// Read data attributes
console.log(element.dataset.productId);     // "123"
console.log(element.dataset.productName);   // "Laptop"
console.log(element.dataset.productPrice);  // "999.99"

// Write data attributes
element.dataset.productDiscount = "10%";

// Check if attribute exists
if (element.dataset.productId) {
  console.log('Has product ID');
}

// Iterate all data attributes
for (const key in element.dataset) {
  console.log(key, element.dataset[key]);
}
</script>
```

**Real-World Example: E-commerce**

```html
<!-- Product list with data -->
<div class="product" 
     data-sku="SKU-001"
     data-price="49.99"
     data-stock="5"
     data-category="electronics">
  <h3>Product Name</h3>
  <button onclick="addToCart(this)">Add to Cart</button>
</div>

<script>
function addToCart(element) {
  const product = element.parentElement;
  const sku = product.dataset.sku;
  const price = product.dataset.price;
  const stock = product.dataset.stock;
  
  if (parseInt(stock) > 0) {
    console.log(`Added ${sku} (${price}) to cart`);
  }
}
</script>
```

**CSS Access to Data Attributes:**

```html
<div data-status="active">Active</div>
<div data-status="inactive">Inactive</div>

<style>
/* Select by data attribute value */
[data-status="active"] {
  background-color: green;
  color: white;
}

[data-status="inactive"] {
  background-color: gray;
  color: white;
}

/* Show data attribute value in CSS */
[data-status]::before {
  content: attr(data-status);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  font-weight: bold;
}
</style>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ data-* attributes store custom data
- ✓ Accessed via element.dataset.attributeName
- ✓ Not visible to users (not displayed)
- ✓ Can be styled with CSS attribute selectors
- ✓ Use for storing metadata, IDs, configurations
- ✓ Don't use for sensitive data
- ✓ Can be modified/added dynamically

---

### Q20: How do you implement keyboard accessibility?

**Answer:**

Keyboard accessibility ensures users can navigate and interact with a website using only the keyboard (important for users with motor disabilities).

**Basic Requirements:**

```html
<!-- 1. All interactive elements must be focusable -->

<!-- ✓ Native interactive elements (focusable by default) -->
<button>Click me</button>
<a href="/">Link</a>
<input type="text">
<select><option>Option</option></select>

<!-- ✗ Non-interactive elements (not focusable) -->
<div>Content</div>
<span>Text</span>

<!-- ✓ Make non-interactive elements focusable with tabindex -->
<div tabindex="0" role="button">Custom button</div>

<!-- ✗ Don't skip tabindex values (confusing) -->
<button tabindex="1">First</button>
<button tabindex="3">Third (breaks order)</button>

<!-- ✓ Use tabindex="0" only (natural tab order) -->
<button tabindex="0">First</button>
<button tabindex="0">Second</button>
<button tabindex="0">Third</button>
```

**Focus Management:**

```html
<!-- Show focus indicator (WCAG requirement) -->
<style>
/* Visible focus indicator */
button:focus {
  outline: 3px solid blue;
  outline-offset: 2px;
}

/* Don't remove focus (bad for accessibility) -->
button:focus {
  outline: none;  /* ✗ BAD */
}

/* Better: Visible focus -->
button:focus {
  outline: 2px solid blue;  /* ✓ GOOD */
}
</style>

<!-- Modal focus trap (focus stays in modal) -->
<div id="modal" role="dialog" aria-modal="true">
  <h2>Dialog</h2>
  <input type="text" id="first-input">
  <button id="close-btn">Close</button>
  
  <script>
  const modal = document.getElementById('modal');
  const firstInput = document.getElementById('first-input');
  const closeBtn = document.getElementById('close-btn');
  
  modal.addEventListener('keydown', function(e) {
    if (e.key === 'Tab') {
      // Trap focus within modal
      if (e.shiftKey && document.activeElement === firstInput) {
        e.preventDefault();
        closeBtn.focus();
      } else if (!e.shiftKey && document.activeElement === closeBtn) {
        e.preventDefault();
        firstInput.focus();
      }
    }
  });
  </script>
</div>
```

**Keyboard Shortcuts:**

```html
<!-- Implement keyboard shortcuts -->
<script>
document.addEventListener('keydown', function(e) {
  // Alt + S to submit form
  if (e.altKey && e.key === 's') {
    e.preventDefault();
    document.querySelector('form').submit();
  }
  
  // Escape to close modal
  if (e.key === 'Escape') {
    const modal = document.getElementById('modal');
    if (modal.open) {
      modal.close();
    }
  }
});
</script>
```

**Skip Links:**

```html
<!-- Help users skip repetitive content -->
<body>
  <!-- Skip to main content (first element) -->
  <a href="#main-content" class="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>
  
  <header>
    <!-- Navigation -->
  </header>
  
  <main id="main-content">
    <!-- Main content -->
  </main>
</body>

<style>
.skip-link {
  position: absolute;
  left: -9999px;  /* Off-screen */
}

.skip-link:focus {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  background: blue;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px;
  z-index: 9999;
}
</style>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Use native interactive elements (button, a, input)
- ✓ Make custom elements focusable with tabindex="0"
- ✓ Show visible focus indicators
- ✓ Manage focus in modals/dynamic content
- ✓ Implement keyboard shortcuts (Alt/Escape)
- ✓ Skip links for repetitive content
- ✓ Tab order should be logical (left-to-right, top-to-bottom)

---

### Q21: What is the template element and how is it used?

**Answer:**

The `<template>` element stores HTML that won't be rendered initially but can be cloned and displayed dynamically via JavaScript.

**Basic Usage:**

```html
<!-- Define template (not visible initially) -->
<template id="card-template">
  <div class="card">
    <h3 class="card-title"></h3>
    <p class="card-description"></p>
    <button class="card-btn">Learn More</button>
  </div>
</template>

<!-- Container for rendered templates -->
<div id="cards-container"></div>

<script>
// Data to render
const items = [
  { title: 'Item 1', description: 'Description 1' },
  { title: 'Item 2', description: 'Description 2' },
  { title: 'Item 3', description: 'Description 3' }
];

// Get template
const template = document.getElementById('card-template');
const container = document.getElementById('cards-container');

// Render each item
items.forEach(item => {
  // Clone template
  const clone = template.content.cloneNode(true);
  
  // Populate data
  clone.querySelector('.card-title').textContent = item.title;
  clone.querySelector('.card-description').textContent = item.description;
  
  // Add to DOM
  container.appendChild(clone);
});
</script>
```

**Benefits:**

```
✓ Content not rendered until needed (performance)
✓ Can be cloned multiple times
✓ Keeps markup clean and organized
✓ Easier to manage complex structures
✓ Reduces DOM duplication
```

**Advanced Example: Complex Template**

```html
<!-- Complex template with slots -->
<template id="user-card">
  <style>
    .user-card {
      border: 1px solid #ddd;
      padding: 15px;
      border-radius: 8px;
    }
    .user-avatar {
      width: 50px;
      height: 50px;
      border-radius: 50%;
    }
  </style>
  
  <div class="user-card">
    <img class="user-avatar" src="" alt="">
    <h4 class="user-name"></h4>
    <p class="user-email"></p>
    <small class="user-role"></small>
  </div>
</template>

<div id="users-list"></div>

<script>
const users = [
  { name: 'John', email: 'john@example.com', role: 'Developer', avatar: 'john.jpg' },
  { name: 'Jane', email: 'jane@example.com', role: 'Designer', avatar: 'jane.jpg' }
];

const template = document.getElementById('user-card');
const list = document.getElementById('users-list');

users.forEach(user => {
  const clone = template.content.cloneNode(true);
  
  clone.querySelector('.user-avatar').src = user.avatar;
  clone.querySelector('.user-name').textContent = user.name;
  clone.querySelector('.user-email').textContent = user.email;
  clone.querySelector('.user-role').textContent = user.role;
  
  list.appendChild(clone);
});
</script>
```

**vs Other Approaches:**

```html
<!-- ✗ String concatenation (security risk) -->
<script>
const html = '<div>' + userInput + '</div>';  // XSS vulnerability
container.innerHTML = html;
</script>

<!-- ✗ Creating elements manually (verbose) -->
<script>
const div = document.createElement('div');
const h3 = document.createElement('h3');
h3.textContent = item.title;
div.appendChild(h3);
container.appendChild(div);
</script>

<!-- ✓ Template approach (clean, safe) -->
<template id="item-template">
  <div>
    <h3 class="title"></h3>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
const clone = template.content.cloneNode(true);
clone.querySelector('.title').textContent = item.title;
container.appendChild(clone);
</script>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Template content is not rendered initially
- ✓ Clone with template.content.cloneNode(true)
- ✓ Populate clone, then add to DOM
- ✓ Cleaner than string concatenation
- ✓ More secure than innerHTML
- ✓ Reusable for lists and dynamic content
- ✓ Can contain styles and scripts

---

### Q22: How do you implement Web Components?

**Answer:**

Web Components are reusable, encapsulated custom HTML elements built with web standards.

**Creating a Simple Custom Element:**

```html
<!-- Define custom element -->
<script>
class CustomButton extends HTMLElement {
  constructor() {
    super();
    // Attach shadow DOM for encapsulation
    this.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' });
  }
  
  connectedCallback() {
    // Render when element added to DOM
    this.render();
  }
  
  render() {
    const text = this.getAttribute('label') || 'Click me';
    const type = this.getAttribute('type') || 'primary';
    
    this.shadowRoot.innerHTML = `
      <style>
        button {
          padding: 10px 20px;
          border: none;
          border-radius: 4px;
          cursor: pointer;
          font-size: 16px;
        }
        
        button.primary {
          background-color: blue;
          color: white;
        }
        
        button.secondary {
          background-color: gray;
          color: white;
        }
        
        button:hover {
          opacity: 0.8;
        }
      </style>
      
      <button class="${type}">
        <slot></slot>
      </button>
    `;
    
    this.shadowRoot.querySelector('button').addEventListener('click', 
      () => this.handleClick());
  }
  
  handleClick() {
    this.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('custom-click', {
      detail: { message: 'Button clicked!' }
    }));
  }
}

// Register custom element
customElements.define('custom-button', CustomButton);
</script>

<!-- Use custom element -->
<custom-button label="Submit" type="primary">
  Submit Form
</custom-button>

<custom-button label="Cancel" type="secondary">
  Cancel
</custom-button>

<!-- Listen to custom events -->
<script>
document.querySelector('custom-button').addEventListener('custom-click', (e) => {
  console.log(e.detail.message);
});
</script>
```

**Example: Custom Card Component**

```html
<script>
class CardComponent extends HTMLElement {
  connectedCallback() {
    this.render();
  }
  
  render() {
    const title = this.getAttribute('title');
    const image = this.getAttribute('image');
    
    this.shadowRoot = this.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' });
    this.shadowRoot.innerHTML = `
      <style>
        .card {
          border: 1px solid #ddd;
          border-radius: 8px;
          overflow: hidden;
          box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
        }
        
        .card-image {
          width: 100%;
          height: 200px;
          object-fit: cover;
        }
        
        .card-content {
          padding: 20px;
        }
        
        .card-title {
          font-size: 20px;
          font-weight: bold;
          margin: 0 0 10px 0;
        }
        
        .card-body {
          color: #666;
          line-height: 1.6;
        }
      </style>
      
      <div class="card">
        <img class="card-image" src="${image}" alt="${title}">
        <div class="card-content">
          <h3 class="card-title">${title}</h3>
          <div class="card-body">
            <slot></slot>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    `;
  }
}

customElements.define('card-component', CardComponent);
</script>

<!-- Use card component -->
<card-component title="Mountain" image="mountain.jpg">
  <p>Beautiful mountain landscape</p>
</card-component>
```

**Lifecycle Methods:**

```javascript
class MyElement extends HTMLElement {
  constructor() {
    super();
    // Called when element is created
    console.log('Created');
  }
  
  connectedCallback() {
    // Called when element added to DOM
    console.log('Connected');
  }
  
  disconnectedCallback() {
    // Called when element removed from DOM
    console.log('Disconnected');
  }
  
  attributeChangedCallback(name, oldValue, newValue) {
    // Called when observed attribute changes
    console.log(`${name} changed from ${oldValue} to ${newValue}`);
  }
  
  static get observedAttributes() {
    // Specify which attributes to observe
    return ['label', 'type'];
  }
}

customElements.define('my-element', MyElement);
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Reusable, encapsulated custom elements
- ✓ Shadow DOM for style encapsulation
- ✓ Lifecycle methods (constructor, connectedCallback, etc.)
- ✓ Slots for content projection
- ✓ Custom events for communication
- ✓ Observed attributes for reactivity
- ✓ Browser-native (no framework needed)

---

### Q23: What are meta tags and what are their common uses?

**Answer:**

Meta tags provide metadata about the HTML document to browsers and search engines. They go in the `<head>` and don't display content.

**Common Meta Tags:**

```html
<head>
  <!-- Character encoding (MUST be first) -->
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  
  <!-- Viewport (responsive design) -->
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  
  <!-- Compatibility -->
  <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
  
  <!-- Search engine optimization -->
  <meta name="description" content="Page description for search results">
  <meta name="keywords" content="keyword1, keyword2, keyword3">
  
  <!-- Open Graph (social media sharing) -->
  <meta property="og:title" content="Page Title">
  <meta property="og:description" content="Description">
  <meta property="og:image" content="image.jpg">
  <meta property="og:url" content="https://example.com">
  <meta property="og:type" content="website">
  
  <!-- Twitter Card -->
  <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image">
  <meta name="twitter:title" content="Title">
  <meta name="twitter:description" content="Description">
  <meta name="twitter:image" content="image.jpg">
  
  <!-- Author and copyright -->
  <meta name="author" content="John Doe">
  <meta name="copyright" content="© 2024 Company">
  
  <!-- Refresh page after 5 seconds -->
  <meta http-equiv="refresh" content="5">
  
  <!-- Disable caching -->
  <meta http-equiv="Cache-Control" content="no-cache, no-store, must-revalidate">
  
  <!-- Theme color (mobile browser) -->
  <meta name="theme-color" content="#000000">
  
  <!-- Apple specific -->
  <meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-capable" content="yes">
  <meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-status-bar-style" content="black">
  <meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-title" content="App Name">
  
  <!-- Robots (SEO crawling) -->
  <meta name="robots" content="index, follow">
</head>
```

**Complete SEO-Optimized Example:**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  
  <!-- Primary Meta Tags -->
  <title>Best Web Development Services - Company Name</title>
  <meta name="title" content="Best Web Development Services">
  <meta name="description" content="Professional web development services including design, backend, and deployment">
  
  <!-- Open Graph / Facebook -->
  <meta property="og:type" content="website">
  <meta property="og:url" content="https://example.com/">
  <meta property="og:title" content="Best Web Development Services">
  <meta property="og:description" content="Professional web development">
  <meta property="og:image" content="https://example.com/og-image.jpg">
  
  <!-- Twitter -->
  <meta property="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image">
  <meta property="twitter:url" content="https://example.com/">
  <meta property="twitter:title" content="Best Web Development Services">
  <meta property="twitter:description" content="Professional web development">
  <meta property="twitter:image" content="https://example.com/og-image.jpg">
  
  <!-- Schema.org / Structured Data -->
  <meta property="schema:name" content="Company Name">
  <meta property="schema:description" content="Web development company">
  
  <!-- Favicon -->
  <link rel="icon" type="image/x-icon" href="/favicon.ico">
  
  <!-- Canonical URL (prevent duplicate content) -->
  <link rel="canonical" href="https://example.com/">
</head>
<body>
  <!-- Content -->
</body>
</html>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Meta tags go in <head>, don't display content
- ✓ charset: Always include UTF-8 encoding
- ✓ viewport: Essential for responsive design
- ✓ description: Used in search results
- ✓ Open Graph: Controls social media previews
- ✓ robots: Control search engine crawling
- ✓ Theme color: Mobile browser UI color
- ✓ Canonical: Prevent duplicate content SEO issues

---

### Q24: How do you handle internationalization (i18n) in HTML?

**Answer:**

Internationalization makes websites accessible in multiple languages and regions.

**Language Declaration:**

```html
<!-- Declare document language -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Welcome</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Welcome</h1>
</body>
</html>

<!-- For mixed languages, specify lang on elements -->
<h1>Welcome</h1>
<p>This is in English</p>
<p lang="es">Bienvenida. Esto es en español</p>
<p lang="fr">Bienvenue. Ceci est en français</p>
```

**Text Direction (LTR/RTL):**

```html
<!-- Left-to-Right (English, most languages) -->
<html lang="en" dir="ltr">

<!-- Right-to-Left (Arabic, Hebrew) -->
<html lang="ar" dir="rtl">

<!-- Specific element direction -->
<p>English text</p>
<p lang="ar" dir="rtl">النص العربي</p>
```

**Handling Different Locales:**

```html
<!-- Different pages for different languages -->
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <!-- Links to alternate language versions -->
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en" href="https://example.com/en/">
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="es" href="https://example.com/es/">
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="fr" href="https://example.com/fr/">
</head>
</html>

<!-- Or use subdomains/subpaths -->
<!-- en.example.com -->
<!-- es.example.com -->
<!-- example.com/en/ -->
<!-- example.com/es/ -->
```

**Locale-Specific Formatting:**

```html
<!-- Date formatting -->
<time datetime="2024-12-24">12/24/2024 (US)</time>
<time datetime="2024-12-24">24/12/2024 (EU)</time>

<!-- Number formatting -->
<span>Price: $1,234.56 (US)</span>
<span>Preço: R$ 1.234,56 (Brazil)</span>

<!-- Currency symbols -->
<span>$99.99 (USD)</span>
<span>€99,99 (EUR)</span>
<span>¥99,99 (JPY)</span>
```

**JavaScript i18n Handling:**

```html
<script>
// Detect user language
const userLanguage = navigator.language || navigator.userLanguage;
console.log(userLanguage); // "en-US", "es-ES", etc.

// Format dates by locale
const date = new Date(2024, 11, 24);
const enDate = date.toLocaleDateString('en-US');  // 12/24/2024
const esDate = date.toLocaleDateString('es-ES');  // 24/12/2024

// Format numbers by locale
const number = 1234.56;
const enNumber = number.toLocaleString('en-US');  // 1,234.56
const deNumber = number.toLocaleString('de-DE');  // 1.234,56

// Format currency by locale
const price = 99.99;
const usCurrency = new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
  style: 'currency',
  currency: 'USD'
}).format(price);  // $99.99

const euCurrency = new Intl.NumberFormat('de-DE', {
  style: 'currency',
  currency: 'EUR'
}).format(price);  // 99,99 €
</script>
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Always declare lang attribute on <html>
- ✓ Use lang attribute for mixed languages
- ✓ RTL languages need dir="rtl" attribute
- ✓ hreflang for alternate language versions
- ✓ navigator.language detects user language
- ✓ Use Intl API for locale-specific formatting
- ✓ Use datetime attribute for time element

---

### Q25: What security considerations are important in HTML?

**Answer:**

HTML security prevents attacks like XSS (Cross-Site Scripting), injection attacks, and data breaches.

**XSS Prevention:**

```html
<!-- ✗ VULNERABLE: User input in HTML -->
<script>
const userComment = getUserComment();  // "<img onerror=alert('XSS')>"
document.innerHTML = "<p>" + userComment + "</p>";  // XSS attack
</script>

<!-- ✓ SAFE: Use textContent (no HTML parsing) -->
<script>
const userComment = getUserComment();
const p = document.createElement('p');
p.textContent = userComment;  // Treated as text, not HTML
document.body.appendChild(p);
</script>

<!-- ✓ SAFE: Escape HTML entities -->
<script>
function escapeHTML(text) {
  const div = document.createElement('div');
  div.textContent = text;
  return div.innerHTML;
}
</script>

<!-- ✓ SAFE: Use template libraries that auto-escape -->
<!-- React, Vue, etc. auto-escape by default -->
```

**Content Security Policy (CSP):**

```html
<!-- Prevent inline scripts and style injection -->
<meta http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy" 
      content="default-src 'self'; 
               script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; 
               style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'">

<!-- Restrict external resources -->
<meta http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy" 
      content="default-src 'self'; 
               img-src 'self' https:; 
               script-src 'self'">

<!-- Report CSP violations -->
<meta http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy" 
      content="default-src 'self'; 
               report-uri https://example.com/csp-report">
```

**CSRF Prevention:**

```html
<!-- Include CSRF token in forms -->
<form method="POST" action="/delete-account">
  <!-- Token sent by server -->
  <input type="hidden" name="csrf-token" value="abc123xyz">
  
  <button type="submit">Delete Account</button>
</form>

<script>
// Verify token on server before processing
</script>
```

**Input Validation:**

```html
<!-- Validate on client-side (not enough!) -->
<input type="email" required>
<input type="number" min="0" max="100">

<!-- But ALWAYS validate on server-side -->
<!-- Client validation is for UX, not security -->
```

**Secure Attributes:**

```html
<!-- rel="noopener noreferrer" for external links -->
<a href="https://external-site.com" 
   rel="noopener noreferrer" 
   target="_blank">
  External Link
</a>
<!-- Prevents window.opener attacks -->

<!-- Sandbox iframes -->
<iframe src="https://untrusted-site.com" 
        sandbox="allow-scripts">
</iframe>

<!-- Sandbox restrictions: no forms, no plugins, no top navigation -->

<!-- Secure forms (HTTPS only, no autocomplete for sensitive data) -->
<form action="https://example.com/submit" method="POST">
  <input type="password" autocomplete="off">
  <input type="text" autocomplete="off">
</form>
```

**Best Practices:**

```html
<!-- 1. Always use HTTPS -->
<meta http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy" content="upgrade-insecure-requests">

<!-- 2. Use security headers -->
<meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
<meta http-equiv="X-Content-Type-Options" content="nosniff">
<meta http-equiv="X-Frame-Options" content="SAMEORIGIN">
<meta http-equiv="X-XSS-Protection" content="1; mode=block">

<!-- 3. Never trust user input -->
<!-- Always escape/validate/sanitize on server -->

<!-- 4. Use HTTPS for all resources -->
<img src="https://example.com/image.jpg">
<link href="https://example.com/style.css">

<!-- 5. Implement CORS properly -->
<meta http-equiv="Access-Control-Allow-Origin" content="https://trusted-domain.com">

<!-- 6. Validate file uploads on server -->
<input type="file" accept=".jpg,.png,.pdf" required>
<!-- Accept attribute helps UX but doesn't prevent attacks -->
```

**KEY POINTS:**
- ✓ Use textContent for user input (not innerHTML)
- ✓ Escape HTML entities
- ✓ Use template libraries (auto-escape)
- ✓ Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
- ✓ Validate forms on client AND server
- ✓ Use rel="noopener noreferrer" for external links
- ✓ Sandbox untrusted iframes
- ✓ Use HTTPS everywhere
- ✓ Never trust user input

---

## Key Takeaways

### HTML Fundamentals
- ✓ HTML provides structure and content
- ✓ CSS handles styling and layout
- ✓ JavaScript adds behavior and interactivity
- ✓ Write clean, semantic HTML

### Best Practices
- ✓ Use semantic elements (not just divs)
- ✓ Proper heading hierarchy
- ✓ Alt text for all images
- ✓ Descriptive link text
- ✓ Accessible forms with labels
- ✓ Valid HTML (use validator)
- ✓ Mobile-first design considerations

### Accessibility
- ✓ Semantic HTML is the foundation
- ✓ Proper labels and ARIA attributes
- ✓ Keyboard navigation
- ✓ Color contrast
- ✓ Alt text for images
- ✓ Test with screen readers

### Performance
- ✓ Defer script loading
- ✓ Lazy load images
- ✓ Use modern image formats
- ✓ Responsive images
- ✓ Minimize inline styles/scripts

### SEO
- ✓ Proper title and meta description
- ✓ Semantic HTML structure
- ✓ Heading hierarchy
- ✓ Descriptive links
- ✓ Structured data (Schema.org)

---

This comprehensive HTML guide covers fundamental to advanced concepts with practical examples and best practices for modern web development.
